2) Architectural decomposition (containers & layers)

Think of the software as 4 layers:

A) UI / Orchestration Layer (Python, external to this zip)

Panel/Bokeh dashboard (python_dash.py) with controls, plots, iteration slider, etc.

Run manager (optim_manager.py) that:

loads config file paths

starts runs

monitors progress

reads back history buffers (coords + metrics)

updates plots live

B) Python ↔ C++ Interop Layer (pybind11 module)

A compiled Python module: placement_engine_py

Exposes a small but powerful API:

set input JSON paths on a Runner

execute() (runs in C++ while releasing the GIL)

zero-copy NumPy “views” over iteration history and metrics

C) Native Optimization Engine (C++)

Coordinates the optimization run and algorithm selection:

Runner → PlacementEngine → LayoutEvaluator

D) Native Data & Math Utilities (C++)

Spatial overlap acceleration grid

Bounding box computation

Normalization + aggregation tools

History storage (preallocated stable buffers)

JSON parsing (nlohmann/json)

3) C++ component HLD (modules, responsibilities, and interfaces)
3.1 Runner (orchestration entry point)

Role: The top-level C++ “job” object.

Key responsibilities:

Load the two JSON files:

jPars : optimizer + objective + constraints + expected params + varList

jBlock : block definitions (and potentially more fields; only width/height/ID are consumed here)

Extract varList (variant selection index per block)

Call into PlacementEngine.load(...)

Execute the run via PlacementEngine.execute()

Design intent: Runner is the “unit of execution” that Python instantiates and controls.

3.2 JsonIO + configuration parsing (input schema → typed config)

Role: Convert JSON dictionaries into a strongly-typed LayoutConfig.

Key responsibilities:

Robust load/save with clear exceptions for missing files / invalid JSON.

Parse blocks into std::vector<Block>:

For each top-level block key, select the variant using varList[i].

Initialize a random (but deterministic-seeded) starting location inside the canvas bounds.

Parse objective weights:

w_area, w_hpwl

Parse constraints (currently 3):

overlap (aggregation + normalization + penalty function selection)

boundary violation (aggregation + normalization + penalty function selection)

aspect violation (scalar normalization + penalty function selection)

Parse optimizer common parameters and exactly one active optimizer:

DE / SA / GA / CNE / PSO

Enforces that exactly one “switch” is enabled.

Penalty function binding design:
A major architectural choice: constraint “type” is bound once at parse-time to a concrete function pointer penalty_fn, so the hot loop (compute_all) does not branch on penalty type repeatedly.

This is a Strategy pattern implemented with function pointers.

3.3 PlacementEngine (algorithm selection + run execution)

Role: The “engine” that owns:

LayoutConfig cfg_

LayoutEvaluator evaluator_

HistoryStore store_
and drives the optimization algorithm.

Key responsibilities:

load(...)

produce config (cfg_)

initialize evaluator with config + store

initialize history store with (num_blocks, max_iters + 1)

execute()

set random seed (Armadillo RNG)

create objective wrapper LayoutObjective

create initial decision vector x = evaluator_.initial_point()

initialize callback (IterationCallback) with stopping criteria and store pointer

choose and run optimizer:

Ensmallen: DE / SA / CNE / PSO

Custom in-house GA path

measure runtime with Stopwatch

mark run complete (optimized_ = true)

Design patterns:

Facade: PlacementEngine is the simplified API for “run placement optimization.”

Strategy: optimizer choice via OptimizerKind active (and optimizer-specific parameter structs).

Observer/Callback: IterationCallback captures each iteration result and records it to HistoryStore.

Important hot-loop boundary:
All optimizers call LayoutObjective::Evaluate(x) repeatedly. Each “StepTaken” callback computes full metrics and records them.

3.4 LayoutEvaluator (the scoring function)

Role: Defines the optimization surface: objective + penalties.

Inputs:

decision vector xy of length 2*n (x,y per block)

widths/heights/areas precomputed from Block list

canvas size and expected aspect ratio

Outputs:

Metrics struct containing:

bbox_area, bbox_aspect

hpwl (currently a global center-based proxy)

overlap (raw overlap area is tracked)

boundary_violation (aggregated)

aspect_ratio_violation

augmented_objective

bbox geometry (cx, cy, w, h)

iteration_index

Computation pipeline inside compute_all(...):

Update block positions from xy

Expand bounding box across rectangles

Track min/max of centers for “HPWL” proxy

Compute boundary violation per rectangle → normalize → aggregate

Compute aspect ratio violation (scalar) → normalize

Compute overlap penalty using OverlapGrid (buffered overlap) → normalize/aggregate

Compute pure objective: w_area * bbox_area + w_hpwl * hpwl

Compute penalties using pre-bound penalty_fn per constraint:

weighted sum of penalty_fn(violation)

Return Metrics with augmented_objective = objective + penalty

Architectural note about HPWL:

The code in this zip computes a single global HPWL-like term: (max cx - min cx) + (max cy - min cy).

Your intended HPWL based on nets/pins would be sum over nets of each net’s bounding box span. That would require adding a netlist model and per-net accumulation in this evaluator.

3.5 OverlapGrid (fast overlap estimation)

Role: Replace naive O(n²) overlap checks with a spatial hashing grid.

Core idea:

Define a grid over a padded region around the canvas.

Insert each rectangle into all grid cells it intersects (with buffer).

For each populated cell, check overlaps among rectangles in that cell.

Deduplicate rectangle pairs that meet in multiple cells using a pair-stamping mechanism.

Aggregate normalized overlap contributions via PenaltyTools.

Performance-oriented design:

Uses stamping (eval_stamp_) to avoid clearing large arrays each evaluation.

Reuses buffers (used_cells_, idx_buf_, pair_values_) to reduce allocations.

Returns an aggregated normalized overlap scalar used by evaluator.

3.6 HistoryStore (stable iteration history + best solution)

Role: Persist iteration-by-iteration placement and metrics for:

offline saving

UI visualization (iteration slider)

best-solution extraction

Key design choices:

Preallocate:

coords_: flattened array length = max_iters * 2 * n

iter_metrics_: length = max_iters

best_coords_: length = 2 * n

This makes memory addresses stable, enabling zero-copy views from Python.

Tracks:

iter_count_ (how many iterations recorded)

best_obj_, best_index_, best_metrics_

“Best” is guarded by conditions (e.g., overlap == 0 and bbox area > 0 in intent).

3.7 IterationCallback (ensmallen callback hook)

Role: Called after optimizer updates coordinates.

Computes metrics with LayoutEvaluator.compute_all(...)

Pushes to HistoryStore

Implements early stopping if stopping_mode == target_objective

Design: This is the “tap” that captures the full optimization trajectory for plotting.

4) pybind11 binding HLD (Python-facing API design)

The Python module exposes Runner as the primary object.

4.1 Execution control

Runner.execute() runs the full optimization and releases the GIL, which is essential so the Panel server can keep responding.

4.2 Zero-copy data access (critical for UI responsiveness)

Bindings expose NumPy array views into C++ buffers:

coords_history() → shape (iters, n, 2)

coords_at(i) → shape (n, 2)

best_coords() → shape (n, 2)

metrics_history() → structured dtype array (iters,) over Metrics

widths() / heights() → (n,)

Why this matters in the HLD:

The UI should not “pull” data by copying large buffers every frame.

Zero-copy allows fast redraws for:

iteration slider scrubbing

time-series plots of metrics

4.3 Lightweight metadata helpers

best_metrics() returns a small dict for convenient consumption.

optimizer_params() returns a dict representation of parsed optimizer configuration.

5) End-to-end runtime flow (sequence view)
5.1 Single run workflow (Python-driven)

User selects jPars and jBlock paths in the Panel UI.

Python creates placement_engine_py.Runner().

Python sets:

runner.jPars_file = ...

runner.jBlock_file = ...

UI triggers runner.execute() (ideally from a worker thread/task so UI stays responsive).

While running:

Optimizer repeatedly calls objective evaluation

Callback stores coords + metrics each iteration

UI periodically reads:

runner.iterations()

runner.metrics_history() (up to current iters)

runner.coords_at(k) for the iteration slider

After completion:

UI uses best_index(), best_coords(), best_metrics() for summary

5.2 CLI workflow (C++ executable)

placement_engine_app <jPars.json> <jBlock.json>

Builds Runner, sets paths, calls execute

(In this zip, output saving is not wired into main; the JSON saver exists in JsonIO, but the run does not currently persist results to expected_params.output_file.)

6) Data model HLD (what data exists and how it moves)
6.1 Primary configuration objects

LayoutConfig

blocks: vector<Block>

objective: ObjectiveConfig(w_area, w_hpwl)

constraints: ConstraintConfig overlap/aspect/boundary

expected: ExpectedParams(canvas, aspect_ratio, overlap_buffer, num_threads, output_file)

optimizer: OptimizerConfig(common + per-optimizer params + active kind + max_iter)

6.2 Runtime state

PlacementEngine

owns config + evaluator + history store

runtime seconds + optimized flag

6.3 History buffers

Coordinates: iteration-major, block-major, xy-minor

Metrics: one struct per iteration

7) How the “augmented objective” is designed (policy view)

The design separates concerns cleanly:

Raw violation measurement

overlap area, boundary overflow distances, aspect ratio deviation, etc.

Normalization

convert to comparable scale (e.g., divide by canvas_area/bbox_area)

Aggregation

sum/max/mean across per-rect or per-pair values

Penalty function

square vs barrier exp/log

Penalty weight

controls constraint importance relative to objective

Objective weights

controls bbox_area vs hpwl tradeoff

This is a strong design because new constraints can follow the exact same pipeline.

8) Extensibility HLD (adding symmetry, deadspace, real HPWL)

Even though symmetry/deadspace aren’t implemented in this zip, the architecture is ready for them:

8.1 Add a new constraint type (general recipe)

To add “symmetry violation” or “deadspace”:

Extend LayoutConfig with:

ConstraintConfig symmetry_c;

ConstraintConfig deadspace_c;

Extend JsonIO::parse_config(...) to parse these constraint nodes.

Extend Metrics to store:

symmetry_violation

deadspace

Extend LayoutEvaluator.compute_all(...) to:

compute raw values

normalize/aggregate if needed

apply bound penalty_fn

add weighted penalty to augmented objective

Extend pybind dtype registration so Python can plot them.

8.2 Real netlist HPWL (what needs to change)

Your intended HPWL requires:

A netlist model:

Nets with multiple pins

Each pin has a block reference + local (dx,dy)

Evaluator needs:

for each net, compute min/max of absolute pin coords across its pins

sum (xmax-xmin)+(ymax-ymin) over nets

Data ownership choice:

parse and store netlist in LayoutConfig, or

store separately in LayoutEvaluator for cache-friendly access

8.3 Deadspace (as you described: polygon envelope – blocks area)

This requires geometry computation beyond bbox:

Build an outline polygon around the union/envelope of rectangles (convex hull or rectilinear hull depending on your definition).

Compute polygon area, subtract total rect area → deadspace.

This fits naturally as another scalar metric + penalty term.

9) Concurrency and responsiveness (HLD for the dashboard)
9.1 What’s already supported

Runner.execute() releases the Python GIL → Python UI thread can remain active.

9.2 What the Panel app should do architecturally

Run execution in a background worker (thread/process) controlled by the “run manager”.

Periodically pull the current iteration count and redraw:

metrics plots (time-series)

placement canvas for selected iteration

9.3 Parallel runs (variant/exploration)

Your earlier description mentions “parallel variant runner” and “parallel exploration runner”. Those headers/sources are not in this zip, but architecturally they would fit as:

ParallelRunner (C++): orchestrates multiple PlacementEngine instances with different configs/variants/seeds

Shared results registry:

per-run best metrics + best coords

status tracking (pending/running/completed)

Python UI:

monitors run statuses

displays top-K best completed placements, updating as runs finish

The existing pybind strategy (zero-copy arrays) is well-suited for scaling this, but you’d likely expose per-run handles or a run table API to Python rather than a single Runner.

10) Build & deployment HLD

Build system: CMake

Outputs:

placement_engine_lib (static library)

placement_engine_app (CLI executable)

placement_engine_py (Python extension module)

Key dependencies:

nlohmann/json (fetched if missing)

Armadillo (linear algebra containers)

ensmallen (optimizers + callback interface)

pybind11 (for Python module)

11) Notable design gaps / mismatches to your stated requirements (so the HLD is accurate)

From the code inside opt.zip:

Only 3 constraints exist: overlap, boundary, aspect ratio.

HPWL is not netlist-based; it’s a global bbox-of-centers proxy.

Output saving to expected_params.output_file is parsed but not clearly wired into a “save results” step.

num_threads exists in config but there is no active multithreading in evaluation.

These are not “bad” in an HLD sense—just important to call out so future design work can land in the right components.
